story: When I was diagnosed with cancer back in 2018, I had a Macmillan nurse in the room with me. That nurse has been with me through my cancer journey, and she is still available today. And thanks to Macmillan I've found a new support network of amazing women who have been through a similar journey. Together they have given me strength and the support needed to take back control of my life and move forward. Macmillan nurses are amazing and make a real difference. This is my very small way of saying 'Thank You' to them all.

story:
It's been a tough year this year for everyone but it's been even worse for amazing charities like Macmillan Cancer Support. They rely heavily on events like fun runs and bake sales to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support.

That 'Virus' will be gone soon enough but sadly Cancer will continue to touch all of our lives at some point for the foreseeable future.

We'd love our wonderful viewers / listeners to just donate a round of drinks or if you're keeping it simply maybe just that couple of pounds you were going to spend on that pint you were going to treat yourself tonight. Just think of all that good your simple donation could do!

Come on, you know it makes sense!

pageSummary: Raising money on behalf of Sally because it was a charity Sally chose to support.
pageSummaryWhat: Raising money on behalf of Sally
pageSummaryWhy: it was a charity Sally chose to support.
story:
Sally asked me to say that she would rather people donated to Macmillan instead of buying flowers.

Sally worked as a volunteer for Macmillan for several years.

She did street collections, met up with other organisations to collect their donations and helped coordinate other volunteers .

Sally was a telephone counsellor, helping others deal with a cancer diagnosis and only stopped because her own cancer diagnosis was making it harder for her.

At the last Macmillan Masked Ball at the Queens Hotel in Leeds, Sally gave an inspiring talk as the main speaker outlining her cancer story.



Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:

pageSummary: A year with no beer!! because they do fantastic work for cancer patients
pageSummaryWhy: they do fantastic work for cancer patients
story:
A year with no beer!!! ...............I never thought I would write these words!

2020 more than any other year has highlighted that we should be thankful for what we have and who we have. We should also be thankful for the freedom we have.

Alcohol for most plays a big part in their lives (including mine), but it's not a necessity. I want to challenge myself like never before.

I have drank regularly for over 20 years and this is probably the biggest challenge I would have ever taken on. I know it is not going to be easy which is why I wanted to do it for a cause that do so much good work towards helping others in need.

Every single penny donated will spur me on, it's not going to be easy but I will do it!!

It really gets you when this horrid illness hits close to home and any help we can do towards the research needed for this illness is greatly appreciated. 

Anyone who knows me, knows this is a massive challenge to me and any donation really will spur me on each day of 2021 to succeed!

Lets do this!!

pageSummary: GMP transport team are raising funds because they supported their Inspector during tough times
pageSummaryWhat: GMP transport team are raising funds
pageSummaryWhy: they supported their Inspector during tough times
story:
GMP Inspector Jon Middleton has triumphantly survived cancer in 2020 and in 2021 returns to GMP and his Transport unit. Whilst Jon does not want the spotlight on him, he does want other cancer patients and their families to be supported in these tough times so that they have the opportunities he did to beat this terrible disease.  To Celebrate Jon's return in January 2021 each Officer will be Running, Cycling or walking (or mix) the same distance as the Metrolink Track they patrol - 63 miles that covers Greater Manchester. In line with current restrictions this exercise must be local to them and recorded by STRAVA with a total of 63 miles individually ran, cycled and/or walked by 31/01/21.  The distance can be done in stages in any mix but must be outdoors regardless of the temperatures or weather. Please help each Officer and our partners taking on this event to raise some much needed funds for a great cause. 

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. story:
My Mum passed away on 11th December 2020 after living with  cancer for 9 years.  She was a very courageous woman who will be sorely missed by her family and friends. Macmillan Cancer Support were there for her throughout that time.

I’m going to try and run 100k during the month of January to raise funds for Macmillan - a mix of outdoors and on the treadmill, depending on weather. This will be a proper challenge for someone who struggled to run a mile at the start of 2020... “Couch to 5k” has a lot to answer for 🤣

story:
As many of you will have seen my brother @grantbarber has taken on a challenge of running a 10km everyday for 24 days in aid of Pancreatic Cancer UK. 

I have decided to join Grant in this challenge and raise some money for Macmillan cancer care Uk. 

We have a personal understanding of what many people like Loz and his family are going through as we lost our mum to cancer in 2005 and I hope people can find some spare change to support the cause.

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

story: GMP Inspector Jon Middleton has triumphantly survived cancer in 2020 and in 2021 returns to GMP and his Transport unit. Whilst Jon does not want the spotlight on him, he does want others cancer patients and families to be supported in these tough times so that they have the opportunities he did to beat this terrible disease.  To Celebrate Jon's return in January 2021 each Officer will be Running, Cycling or walking (or mix) the same distance as the Metrolink Track they patrol - 63 miles that covers Greater Manchester. In line with current restrictions this exercise must be local to them and recorded by STRAVA with a total of 63 miles individually ran, cycled and/or walked by 31/01/21. pageSummaryWhat: Giving up drinking alcohol for 6 months
pageSummaryWhy: Of the wonderful support they gave my Nana
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising for MacMillan. I am giving up alcohol from the 9th January until the 9th of July in memory of my Nana.  

My Nana Millie was a strong, caring, loving and independent woman who, at the age of 91 was diagnosed with lung Cancer.  In her final months, the Macmillan nurses were wonderful, always there for support and they really made a difference to Millie.

Cancer is a horrible disease that devastates lives and families and it’s my hope that by giving up alcohol for 6 months we will not only raise money for a fantastic cause, but also highlight how healthy living can contribute to the battle against Cancer.

Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. eventName: Alan's 50 years on this earth challenge
pageSummary: I will be 50 this year and want to do something because Macmillan helped my family at our lowest point
pageSummaryWhat: I will be 50 this year and want to do something
pageSummaryWhy: Macmillan helped my family at our lowest point
story: Hi this year I will be 50 and I want to do something positive to remember the year by. So I have decided to do a virtual walk, crawl etc from Lands End to John O'Groats during the course of this year and lose weight at the same time. I have from the 01/01/21 to the 31/12/21 to complete my challenge. I will post postcards along the way and will give you updates on my Facebook page. The reason why I have chosen Macmillan Cancer is because they helped my family when we didn't have a penny to our name due to my father being diagnosed with cancer and not being able to work. They told us where we could get help and how we could help ourselves, without them I honestly do not know what would have happened. My dad fought cancer for 21 plus years, always with a smile on his face. He is no longer with us in person but is never out of our thoughts and always in our hearts. I totally understand if you can't give in these very challenging times but if you can it would help a great cause and encourage me on my journey from one end of the country to the other. Thank you Alan
title: Alan's Alan's 50 years on this earth challenge

story:
I have decided to set myself a massive challenge in 2021 and to help me through this challenge and keep me motivated I will be raising money for Macmillan Cancer Support. 

The challenge is to run the distance of the Wales Coastal Path 🏃with #runendtoend, a total of 870 miles, starting on 1st January 2021 and completing the challenge sometime on or before 31st Dec 2021. 

I will be posting regular updates on my Just Giving page so please opt in to follow my progress and cheer me on!

You can also join in the fun...Have a go at guessing the day you think I will complete the challenge. Pick any day in 2021 and write the date in the comment box. Keep an eye out for the regular updates... I may even find a prize for the nearest correct answer! 🏆

pageSummary: running 300km between Jan 1st and Feb 28th 2021 because I turn 40 on the 28th of Feb.
pageSummaryWhy: I turn 40 on the 28th of Feb.
story:
I will turn 40 on the 28th of February.  I have spent the last year working towards a target of going into my 40th year the fittest and healthiest I have ever been.  To complete this goal I am planning to run 300km (~186 miles) between January 1st and February 28th 2021.  This is the equivalent of running 7 marathons in 8 weeks.

I have decided to do this final push more publicly given the final 2 months will likely be the hardest due to the weather and the general post Christmas slump.

Along with my personal goal, I have decided to do this final stretch as a fundraiser for Macmillan Cancer Support as they have supported family and loved ones in tough times.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. 

I am going to run/walk 100 miles in the 31 days of January, to raise money & awareness for The British Heart Foundation! The aim is to help raise money to support the charity and anyone effected by heart and circulatory diseases & from your donations big & small, you are helping too!

 I will be completing this challenge for my Bampy who sadly passed away in November under care for the 20+ years of his life and without the amazing work carried out by the wonderful people in the hospitals and charities, I would of never got the chance to see or even meet him.

So please donate whatever you can to help me raise as much as possible to give to this fantastic cause that I strongly believe in as did my Bampy

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

pageSummary: Being a sensible human because We haven't been sensible humans for a few years
pageSummaryWhy: We haven't been sensible humans for a few years
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page

The lovely Jon Jones and I have been drinking more than our fair share of alcohol for the past few years. It has been an enjoyable past time but we both see a need to change our routine and our habits around alcohol. We are doing this anyway and do not expect anyone to donate, we will be donating £100 to my brothers just giving page  at the end of the month regardless but thought we would start a page of our own in case any of you guys feel the urge to donate too. My incredible brother is the one who kickstarted our motivation to make this change. 

Personally my alcohol intake has been pretty awful since my awesome Dad passed away in April. Being very honest I haven't had a day off since. We are not doing this as new years resolution or anything, we are hopefully changing our views on what alcohol means to us. We will be going down to one day per week and using January to donate to keep us motivated. 

Dad passed away partly due to an undiagnosed heart condition and we have chosen this charity in his name.

Thanks for reading xxx

story:
Hey!

I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation, here is a little video  (https://www.instagram.com/p/CJdeTEABdDw/?igshid=lx8cxihgacpo) about why this cause is so important to my family and I.

I will be taking part in the virtual Camino de Santiago challenge where I will be running, cycling and rowing the equivalent distance which is a mega 480.9 miles in 4 months. 

I'll be keeping you updated with my 'virtual' location on the challenge, so feel free to check out updates on my Instagram - @tashathon

The British Heart Foundation have helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly, 460 people still die each day from heart and circulatory disease. BHF need our support to create new treatments and discover new cures.

Any amount, big or small means so much, lets continue to break heartbreak forever and fight for every heartbeat.

Thank you so much,

Natasha xoxo

story:

Research by the BHF means that the lives of some of my dearest people have been improved, or even saved. 

It is no secret that alcohol is a bit of a bug- bear of mine! I completed Dry January last year and made huge improvements - but then.... Well 2020 happened and I lost a lot of the ground I gained. 

So I'm going again in 2021 - committing publicly last year gave me so much support and raised valuable funds too. So I am asking everyone for their support again this year. Please pledge the cost of one drink - a beer (or a 4 pack) a glass of wine (or a bottle 😉) and help me help the BHF. Thank you

story:
Two weeks ago today I received the heart breaking news that one of my best friends had passed away unexpectedly. Since then I've been blown away by the love, strength and positivity that her amazing family and our brilliant friends have shown.

Ten years ago I started running. I loved it. I also hated it some days but generally I loved it... I got quite good at it and ran in events
that developed into a whole host of crazy fitness challenges. Shaz was one of my biggest supporters and was proud of me for everything I achieved over that time.

Injury and other difficulties took over and these days all I run is a bath... so I am sorting my shit out and in 2021 and in Shaz’s memory I will be starting again. To give me a kick start I'm signing up for the Great Run Accumulator with an aim of running 50 miles in January.

In doing so I’ll be raising money for the British Heart Foundation again in Sharon's name.

Any donations will be really appreciated as will any support and accountability as this won't be easy for me.

Anyone is also more than welcome to join me, albeit virtually with more information being found at www.greatrun.org/virtual-running/accumulator/january

Wish me luck. I’m going to need it!

eventName: Kirstie runs 5k a day for a year
story:
So, Colleagues from work have taken on and completed running 5k a day for a year, I joined in on a few runs throughout the year and have decided to take over from Jan 1st 2021 and also run 5k a day for a year! I know...madness! I’m preparing myself for lots of tears and hard times but I know my friends and family and knowing I am raising money for such an amazing cause it will keep me going.

I have chosen the British heart foundation for my friend Amie, a charity that is so close to hers and her families hearts. I know that Amie has wanted to raise money for the BHF for a long time now but has been quite unwell herself to start anything. When Amie is better I know she will join me on a few runs and keep me going throughout the year. I couldn’t think of a better charity or family to do this for and I hope I make your dad proud just like you do everyday. This is for you Pete! 

Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!
title: Kirstie runs 5k a day for a year

pageSummary: I am fundraising because I lost my dad at the start of March in 2020
pageSummaryWhy: I lost my dad at the start of March in 2020
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

The BHF means a lot to me personally as not only did my dad pass at the start of March in 2020 my mum also had a stroke at the very start of 2020 so I am fundraising for both of them.

story:
Anyone that knows me well knows that keeping fit and active is very important to me. They also know that I love nothing more than to moan about my seemingly never-ending list of injuries. I’ve suffered from hip and back pain for 6 years now following a failed hip arthroscopy surgery back in 2015. I’ve spent the last few years cycling through various doctors, scans and physiotherapists to chase a diagnosis and find the elusive ‘quick fix’ that must be out there. The reality is that as time has passed and I have learnt more about my anatomy, I’ve had to accept that this kind of chronic orthopaedic pain does not always come with simple explanations or fixes. I’ve had multiple diagnoses including mild hip dysplasia, retroverted femur, FAI & facet joint degeneration; all of which contribute to a complex anatomy that essentially pisses off my hips and lower back.

Ultimately, I now manage this pain is through modifying activity and being consistent with physio plans (which anyone that’s done physio will know is a ball-ache at the best of times). This means avoiding or limiting high impact sports like long-distance running, football, squash etc. Whilst this is very frustrating being an active guy in my 20’s, I realise that it could be much worse and that there are plenty of people with way more restricted mobility than me.

So what the hell does this have to do with the Bournemouth Pier to Pier swim? Since I’ve come to accept (for now) that I can’t go for runs or play high impact sports as much as I’d like to, I’ve been looking for an outlet where my half-assed excuse for a hip can thrive. And I figured that it doesn’t get much more low impact than swimming!

This is probably a good time to mention that one month ago, I could not swim more than 6 lengths front crawl without gasping for breath and wondering why my shoulders were on fire. However my dad persuaded me to book onto a total immersion swimming lesson with an instructor called James Ewart, and it ended up being far more valuable than I envisaged. A few days after the lesson I managed 50 lengths of front crawl (albeit far from perfectly) with controlled breathing and almost no shoulder pain. To celebrate, I did what any sensible person would do after having one successful lesson – and decided to book on to the Bournemouth Pier 2 Pier race. I also decided that instead of suffering through it alone, I would drag my mate Alex down with me.

So here we are, six months away from our 1.5 mile sea swim, in the middle of a global pandemic and with all the pools shut. Aside from trying to become better swimmers, we're also doing this to raise money for the British Heart Foundation who are more desperate than ever for new funding. The COVID-19 pandemic has cut their ability to fund new research in half, so it would be massively appreciated if you could help make a small but meaningful contribution, in return for us swallowing a gallon of seawater.
title: Bournemouth Pier to Pier Swim

story:

The challenge:

Run 603 miles in 2021. 

Rules:

Minimum 1 mile a day. Absolutely no skip days and no excuses.

I will triple all donations made to this point. All of them. Even if somehow this blows up and it costs me my entire life savings. This goes for if I miss a single day, or if I miss the overall target.

story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

Earlier this year, the unthinkable happened when both D & L were injured in an accident at home. Thankfully Bristol Children’s hospital were amazing, but Lawson had to be referred to GOSH for further specialist treatment. The little man has undergone 6 procedures this year, all during a pandemic 🤦‍😬 Amazingly at GOSH, they have a patient hotel to stay in free of charge while waiting to be admitted - something that is even more useful when hotels are shut! This isn’t the end of the treatment road for Lawson, so it would be amazing to raise some money to help out him and other families in the future!

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Following a dire 2020 for everyone, this January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity).

I’m aiming to run 100 miles throughout the month to raise money for the hospitals life saving work. Over 600 children arrive in the hospital daily, and COVID has made this year more difficult for all these kids and their families. 100% of your donations will go to the Hospital charity and your money will help to fundgroundbreaking research, advanced medical equipment, child and family support services, and the rebuilding and refurbishment of wards and medical facilities.

Aiming to have mates join along the way for some of the runs however if you fancy joining for any of the runs in the cold and wet weather in Glasgow then give me a shout.

pageSummary: Bazz and I are running 31 miles during January because they are a charity very close to our hearts <U+0001F495>
pageSummaryWhat: Bazz and I are running 31 miles during January
pageSummaryWhy: they are a charity very close to our hearts <U+0001F495>
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Bazz and I have decided to take part in ‘running off Christmas’ to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital, a charity very close to our hearts.

Thanks to GOSH, we’ve been able to enjoy a wonderful Christmas at home and to say that we’ve overindulged is an understatement......it’s going to take some running off 😂.We’re going to be off alcohol and running a total of 31 miles each during January.Not much of a problem for Bazz but he’s going to have to drag/push me through every single one of those miles....

Wish us luck!!And if you do have any spare change for sponsorship, we’d be incredibly grateful.I’m going to need the motivation to get me over the line!!!

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story: When I was 15 months old, I was taken into GOSH for major head surgery for a condition called Dual-Craniosynostosis. This has caused me visual impairment and could’ve led to more serious impairments if it had gone untreated. The surgery consisted of my head being cut open from my left ear, over the top of my head and down to my right ear. Parts of my skull were then cut away and repositioned. I still have pieces of metal in my head to help hold my skull together. I had a bandage around my head like a helmet to protect my head and the swelling. I was in intensive care for 3 days monitoring blood loss. After coming out of ICU I was in hospital for a few weeks but recovered well under great Ormond streets care with routine appointments until I was 13. I’ve got a massive scar on my head, and hair permanently missing but I love it. It shows the journey I’ve been on and how far I’ve come! So this January I will be taking part in Running off Christmas. I will be running 31 miles in 31 days, to raise money to give back to Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Without Great Ormond Street Hospital, I genuinely wouldn’t be the person I am today. Knowing how much they’ve helped me and knowing that there are so many more children in need of the same help, most of those with conditions far worse than mine. It would mean a great deal to me if you could help me help them.

story:
This January, I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity).

Since my daughter was born earlier this year, like any new parent, I’ve had my own anxieties about her becoming poorly, particularly with Covid being so prevalent and in our minds. I hope we never need to use their services but knowing there are amazing children’s hospitals out there does provide some comfort. Our family have needed to use the services of GOSH before as when my youngest sister was a toddler, she needed surgery at GOSH and they were brilliant. 

I’ve always enjoyed running but since giving birth I’ve not done much in the way of exercise at all! So when I saw this challenge I thought it would be perfect to get me back into exercise but also raise money for a hospital who does such amazing work with/for our children. 

31 miles will definitely be a challenge, especially as the days are cold and dark, but I will do it.

After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most.It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

Earlier this year, the unthinkable happened when both D & L were injured in an accident at home. Thankfully Bristol Children’s hospital were amazing, but Lawson had to be referred to GOSH for further specialist treatment. The little man has undergone 6 procedures this year, all during a pandemic 🤦‍😬 Amazingly at GOSH, they have a patient hotel to stay in free of charge while waiting to be admitted - something that is even more useful when hotels are shut! This isn’t the end of the treatment road for Lawson, so it would be amazing to raise some money to help out him and other families in the future!

pageSummary: Bringing families close to their poorly children because Please read our story <U+0001F64F>
pageSummaryWhat: Bringing families close to their poorly children
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page  .

Leon and I will be participating in the ‘Running off Christmas’ this January which entails running a mile a day (31 miles in total) to raise money for this amazing cause that is so close to our hearts. With the money that is raised for the charity, Leon and I was able to stay really close to the hospital where Oliver was being treated. It costs around £900 a month to keep a family in accommodation by the hospital in the centre of London. In total we have been there nearly 6 months over the 5 years of Oliver’s life. So we would be so grateful if you guys can support us in donating a little something to help us reach our target for this fantastic hospital. Without them, we wouldn’t be where we are today 🙏


Our story...

We found out about Oliver’s heart condition (tetralogy of fallot) at my 20 week scan which shook our world to say the least! It was a week before Christmas in 2013. We was transferred to the John Radcliffe in Oxford the next day for a more in depth heart scan. We were given lots of information that evening and choices including the worst case which is every parents nightmare. Then at 22 weeks my waters broke and our world was thrown up side down. Fortunately, Oliver held on with limited waters and was born 6 weeks later at the John Radcliffe by an emergency C section, where he was kicking and screaming which we then knew we had a fighter on our hands. Oliver was really poorly and it was touch and go for which seemed like a life time. Then at 4 weeks old (32 weeks gestation) he was transferred to GOSH. He was the smallest baby on CICU at 1.2kg. Few days later on the Saturday morning, he had 2 cardiac arrests, the second he was gone for 6 mins (our world crumbled but we had all our faith in the team). Once again he came back fighting and on the Tuesday morning he had his life saving operation (there was no other choice which either we turned off his life support or go a head with the operation). He was the smallest baby worldwide to have a stent procedure through his tiny leg artery to his heart at 1.2kg!

Fast forward nearly 5 years where Oliver has undergone 4 more stent procedures, 2 open heart surgery’s and Oliver has just recovered from his 3rd open heart op nearly 6 weeks ago where they did a valve replacement. We owe everything to the team at GOSH to allow us to have Christmas at home as a family. 

Thank you for reading and any donation would be so grateful to us all xx


Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Please follow our journey over the next 12 months to see how we get on . #MDC2021Challenge

pageSummaryWhy: In memory and celebration of Stephen’s life.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

This year, 2020, Stephen Saxon was taken from us all after his brave battle with cancer.  It has been a very hard year and one that would have been so much easier with him here keeping us all amused.

Next year, on 15th January 2021, we shall be celebrating what would have been his 65th birthday and we wish to mark the day in a special way.  So, we have decided to collectively walk 65km between 1st-15th January, with all kind sponsorship donations being made to Cancer Research UK.

We have set the bar at 65km as this is achievable, but our intention is to exceed this, weather permitting.  We shall record distances walked on a daily basis, by whatever means used by individuals.

We would love it if you could support us and thank you for your interest.

pageSummary: Let's finish the year on a positive note <U+0001F495> because it has been a tough one for us all.
pageSummaryWhat: Let's finish the year on a positive note <U+0001F495>
pageSummaryWhy: it has been a tough one for us all.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

2020, you started out so promisingly. After 20+ years of talking about it and a last minute gin fuelled application, I got accepted to do my Primary PGDE. Then it just went downhill from there.

Covid hit, home learning, Google Classroom and working at the education hub became the norm and life just took on a slower pace. We enjoyed family walks, baking and just spending time together. Schools went back, I started uni and life seemed to be slowly getting back to "normal".

September came, Aberdeen went into lockdown again and my life turned upside down. Overnight my days became hospital visits and phone calls and Mum became my number one priority. I quickly realised uni would need to wait and deferred to restart next year, looking after Mum was my job now. Sadly things didn't go as planned and Mum didn't get to spend the time at home with family and friends that she had wanted. What Mum and I did get though was one last outing along Stonehaven beach in the sunshine, something so simple but a memory that I will treasure forever. The next few months were a rollercoaster as I watched my wonderful Mum slowly get taken from us, along with a wee health scare of my own thrown in for good measure. The year was not done with me though and a week after my amazing Mum passed away, Covid entered our house and isolation started. The timing was beyond cruel, snatching away our final chance to say goodbye to our loving Mum, Granny and Mother-In-Law 💔

So well done 2020, you broke me but you also showed me I am stronger than I ever thought I could be. As I go in to 2021, I am leaving behind the 💩 and moving forward with treasured memories and the reminder that I have the most amazing friends and family around me. Thank you to all of you who have helped me through the last few months with advice, loaning of equipment, food parcels, uni notes, baking, flowers, gifts, messages, phone calls, video calls and doorstep visits. Most of all though thank you to Eddy and my girls, who have been amazing I look forward to making lots more happy memories with you all in 2021 🥰

If any of you would like to finish this horrible year on a positive note, I have set up a donation page to Cancer Research in the hope that their research can help stop another family go through the cruel pain of cancer.

Thank you again & a happy new year to all of you 🎉 Hold your loved ones close, live every day as if it's your last and may your 2021 be a happy and healthy one 😘

So 2020 has been really crappy! I was thinking of ways to doing something positive in 2021.
I am going to try and raise as much money as I can for Macmillan and Cancer research.

I have decided to do 50 challenges over the year. 1) the 50 k in 10 day Macmillan challenge in feb 2) Cambridge half marathon 3) run lands end to John o groats over the year!! 4) dry Jan, probably the hardest challenge seeing as schools might not go back til .....
Then small things like 1) a kindness to a stranger every day 2) ring a friend or family member I haven’t spoken to in a while every week. 3) cook a meal for an elderly/ single/ someone once a month.
Anyway, I am struggling to think of stuff and then thought might be fun if friends set me a challenge? Be kind!

I know the charities and science research is going to take a huge hit this year and we can see what happens when money and scientists get together. Roll on a vaccine and a happier 2021!

Loads of love to all and happy, healthy and fun new year!

pageSummary: I am raising money because I want to honour someone who has battled cancer!
pageSummaryWhy: I want to honour someone who has battled cancer!
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

My sister Rosemary and I have decided to do this challenge for 2021 to raise as much money as possible for a very worthwhile cause, Cancer Research UK.

Over the years I, like many others have had family members and friends inflicted with this horrific disease and I hope by raising money for them, they will be a step closer to hopefully one day eradicating cancer for good.

I think everyone can agree that 2020 was an exceptionally difficult year for everyone however there is 1 person in particular that faced the most horrific year!

On the 29 April 2020 my step children’s mum, Debbie received the potential life changing news that she had triple negative breast cancer. On top of everything COVID, she now had to face this horrific disease in the midst of the pandemic. This required her to endure chemotherapy followed by surgery followed by radiotherapy. Well she faced it head on and done it for herself and her kids. On the 17 December 2020 Debbie rang that bell of hope as she left the Beatson cancer free!

I am in awe of the courage she has shown throughout her treatment. She very firmly pulled up her big girl pants and kicked cancers ass and she is here to tell the tale.

So we are going to run/walk the distance of Lands End to John O Groats (874 miles) starting 01/01/2021 and will be completed before or on 31/12/2021! I am doing this in honour of Debbie and of all the others having to face this horrific disease.

Any donation, no matter how small will be very gratefully received

Thank you 😊

pageSummary: I am running because I want to see an end to Cancer.
pageSummaryWhy: I want to see an end to Cancer.
story:
For those of you who know me well, it's no surprise to find that I like to have a challenge to focus on and motivate me. I've completed two half marathons for Cancer Research UK in the past but lost the running bug until earlier this year, when I laced my trainers up once more and completed the Couch to 5k programme for the second time.

As well as losing my fitness over the past few years, I have also lost family and friends to Cancer. However, I have also seen how advances in research and treatment have helped others I know. 2021 is the year to do something positive and raise some money so life-changing research can continue.

Running the length of the UK means covering 1083 miles in 2021. This is going to be a tough one for me - keeping up the consistency and motivation throughout the year (as well as finding the time) is going to be challenging - but if it wasn't a real challenge, I wouldn't feel able to ask people to donate the odd pound or two.

1 in 2 people will get cancer in their lifetime. Please help me to contribute to improving the chances of individuals beating this horrible disease. Every pound donated will help and will be greatly appreciated by me. x x x

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

2020 has been a difficult year for all and especially for charities with Covid-19 significantly reducing the amount of fundraising taking place. Thus, I wanted to utilise the fact that Covid-19 has allowed me to work from home on some days throughout December. So the fuel I have saved from not completing my regular commute I plan to donate to Cancer Research UK.

On top of this I will also be taking advantage of the increased generosity of Cadent's matched giving programme to quadruple the value of donations made meaning Cadent will Match £4 for every £1 Donation Made until 31st December 2020 (up-to £1600 for each employee).

story:
After having a recent scare I felt very fortunate to be one of the lucky ones receiving good news. I became very aware that not everyone in that waiting room would have been in the same position as me and I felt the need to do something to contribute towards beating this horrible disease. 

To raise money I have decided to run a marathon over January. That's 26.2 miles which for a very unfit person carrying more than my fair share of Christmas weight will definitely prove to be a challenge! Especially in the cold. Anyone who knows me, knows that I'm a wimp in the cold.

Please donate whatever you can. Thank you.

story:
We want our 2021 to start on a positive - healthier, happier, active and together albeit apart. 

So many charities have lost out on funding this year due to cancelled events and restrictions so we wanted to do our little bit to help whilst doing something that would challenge each of us. 

Our team is built up of a group who want to be more active during a challenging time. What better way to do this than in a team. Together we will travel the length of the uk weather it’s walking, running on a bike or cross trainer or in a home gym lifting more weights than before.

story: Larry's Grandchildren are aiming to run/ walk a minimum of 500 miles (800km) in January to raise funds for Marie Curie. Marie Curie supported our Grandad through his cancer journey, ultimately allowing him to stay at home during the pandemic and pass away peacefully surrounded by his family. We are raising funds as a thank you to Marie Curie and as a tribute to our Grandad, who we were all very close to

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

As we are unable to hold our usual New Year's Day ride in Bellaghy, this year Antrim Chase are holding an online fundraiser in memory of Ray Graham who passed away peacefully at home earlier this year. 

Ray dedicated her life to supporting others and over the years has raised more than one million pounds for Marie Curie. Every year Antrim Chase join with Ray to host the Annual Bellaghy Gymkhana and each winter Ray and her family welcome riders from far and wide to their home in Bellaghy to set off for our wonderful New Year's Ride. 

As we are all missing out on the thrills and spills of our legendary Bellaghy ride, we hope this year instead that you will join us to raise much needed funds for an important charity and in memory of a very special lady.

story:
With the blessing of Wendy's husband Stephen and her daughters Rachael and Helen; Lizzie will be walking and jogging 50 miles in January for Marie Curie, in memory of Wendy. 

Lizzie aims to raise as much as possible in January for this charity who are so important at such a difficult time in many people's lives. 

During her walks and jogs, Lizzie will be mindfully focusing on her love of nature and wildlife and aiming to share updates and photos of her walks. Something that Lizzie feels Wendy would appreciate, as she knows just how much she loved being in her garden and looking after wildlife.

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

pageSummary: Running the Edinburgh Half marathon because They cared for my beautiful big sister <U+2764>
pageSummaryWhy: They cared for my beautiful big sister <U+2764>
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

My beautiful big sister spent her final few months being cared for by the Marie curie before she passed away with is all by her side in September 2020.

Angela sadly passed away due to metestatic breast cancer aged 46 leaving her beloved girls Megan and Amy. Along with her much loved Husband Mark. 

Through out her life and career Angela always cared for others and was a fantastic nurse.  She found it hard being the patient but the staff at the Marie Curie cared for my sister with such care, affection and dignity. Right up to the end Angie worried about the well being of the staff looking after her!

Angie was a fighter to the end and for those that know me will know that this is a challenge for me. And I'm sure Angie will be having a giggle with Dad at the thought of me running a half Marathon but they will give me the strength and the Marshall fighting spirit to complete the distance.

Covid has seen a massive drop in charity donations and this wonderful charity supports patients and their families with terminal illness. If you can afford a pound or two I will be forever greatful.

Angie LYTTMAB always and forever

story: The rnli have continued to look after us through difficult and unsure times. Usually at this time of the year i would be getting ready to jump off the rhu marina pontoons but this year everything has changed. This has meant that the rnli have not been able to raise the money they usually do this year which really is not fair on them after the efforts they have put in to keeping everyone safe. In light of this i have decided to do a similar thing to usual by jumping in tomorow to hopefully raise at least a little money for the rnli. I would REALLY appreciate even a little donation towards their amazing work this year. Thank you and have a happy new year !

story:
Our annual fund raiser to chip up your used Christmas trees at the lifeboat centre in Walmer Kent. Because of covid and social distancing we have set up this page to do whatever we can to keep you safe. Please give generously and stay safe 

Any questions call Tom on 07833447849 

Here is their story...........

Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.Thank you.

pageSummary: Hi, I'm Cairo and i am doing a fundraising walk because I love wildlife.
pageSummaryWhat: Hi, I'm Cairo and i am doing a fundraising walk
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
pageSummary: I am doing a cake sale because my life has always had animals in.
pageSummaryWhat: I am doing a cake sale
pageSummaryWhy: my life has always had animals in.
story:
Ever since I was a toddler, I have been surrounded by dogs and cats. In 2019, when I was eight, I heard about what was happening to the animals on a David Attenborough program. I was shocked when I heard that only two white rhinos were left in the whole world due to poaching. I was so sad I cried through the rest. Christmas came and as one of my presents, I had a Rhino adoption from WWF for 2020.Now my Rhino adoption is over and as a new resolution I plan to put every thing into saving the animals of the world around school. I plan to do a series of cake sales.

Please donate to my cause.

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

pageSummary: I am running the Royal Parks half marathon because I want to raise money to support their work.
pageSummaryWhat: I am running the Royal Parks half marathon
pageSummaryWhy: I want to raise money to support their work.
story:
In 2020, starting with lockdown in March, we spent a lot more time outdoors enjoying what our immediate surroundings had to offer. We got up early in spring to listen to the dawn chorus. We watched more closely as the seasons changed in our garden and neighbourhood.

I ran in parks, around fields and through woods, getting fitter and enjoying my surroundings. 2020 made me feel more connection to my neighbourhood and to the natural world. In 2021 I want to play my part in safeguarding that for everyone. I'm starting by signing up to run the Royal Parks half marathon in aid of WWF.

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
pageSummary: I am walking/running 200km this January because this motivates me to exercise and help others too
pageSummaryWhy: this motivates me to exercise and help others too
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:
Happy 2021! UCL Friends of MSF has created a fun activity for you - decide your own January challenge!

Over the past year, despite the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, less developed countries faced humanitarian crisis and MSF has not stopped providing healthcare to people in need and ensuring that resources have been reached to areas with crippled healthcare systems. To counter all the doom and gloom of this year, here are some positive news stories of MSF successes: Eight Inspiring MSF Stories from 2020. 

We have created a list of resources to help you meditate, get in shape, read more or whatever other goals you've decided to reach this year! Post about your challenge on social media an get your friends to donate to MSF to motivate you to keep it up!

Sponsorship form: https://forms.gle/Yq1wJhpPReePtMHx9

pageSummary: I am drinking only water from 01 - 31 January 2021 because access to clean water and sanitation is key.
pageSummaryWhat: I am drinking only water from 01 - 31 January 2021
pageSummaryWhy: access to clean water and sanitation is key.
story:
I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January.

I spent a lot of lockdown staring out the window thinking about the people in the arid parts of Ethiopia, favellas of Brazil and the slums of Bangladesh and many other very poor areas and countries, and how coronavirus is affecting them. This is me doing my bit to try and provide soap and clean water to those people during this extremely unprecedented global challenge.

I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

pageSummaryWhy: we want others to have the gift of clean water
story:
Just Water is the ultimate detox after an over-indulgent Christmas. Azariah and I will be giving up coffee, beer, wine, juice and other delights in an attempt to only drink water this January.

We are fundraising for WaterAid because we want to help change lives with the gift of clean water. Money goes towards the Future on Tap appeal to provide clean water to those who don’t have it.

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across the world.
